From the results of the FDTD computation in \cite{Katz_FDTD_Analysis_Horn_Antennas}, \cite{Balanis_Finite-difference_time-domain_antenna_radiation} and \cite{Tirkas_Contour_Path_FDTD_Pyramidal_Horns_E_Plane} show good agreement with measured patterns in all regions including the broad range of low response backward region. However, this computation were for small horn compared to these used in \cite{Rudduck_hp_horn} and \cite{Mentzer_s_diff}. The numerical techniques require large computational resources and time. This becomes more acute for large horns. However, from the FDTD results of \cite{Katz_FDTD_Analysis_Horn_Antennas}, \cite{Balanis_Finite-difference_time-domain_antenna_radiation} and \cite{Tirkas_Contour_Path_FDTD_Pyramidal_Horns_E_Plane}, it is clear that the claim in \cite{Mentzer_s_diff} that \lq\lq The computed patterns may indeed be more accurate than the measured pattern because of the possible experimental errors such as leakage, reflections from feed, and mount structures, etc., for this low field level ($\approx 60$ dB below main beam maximum)\rq\rq is not true.


A pure GTD formulation that gives good results in all regions remains an attractive proposition because it gives the physical picture and because it would require insignificant computer time and resources (as compared to purely numerical technique). 

From all this discussions it is seen that GTD formulation have till now failed in the backward broad range of low response regions because the finiteness of the edges were not incorporated in the diffraction coefficient used. The problem of diffraction by the edge of an infinite half-plane/wedge is a canonical problem in GTD. GTD offers an asymptotic solution to this problem. Because, of this the GTD formulations having these canonical problem as their base have failed till date, wherever finiteness of the edges plays an important rule. In GTD formulation, finite edge would mean a corner discontinuity. In order to incorporate this finite effect in the horn problem, corner diffraction needs to be considered.


